{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17598284","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17598284"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:35:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:35:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15460"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15460","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15460"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.11,0,0.09,0.77]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8151"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61471"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8151","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8151"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15460"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"46922"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4487"},{"type":"tags","id":"4907"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"9869"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19749"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19752"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61471","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/61471"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EStarling forces control fluid movement between the intravascular and interstitial compartments.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is most likely to cause peripheral oedema?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Decreased plasma volume","Decreased capillary hydrostatic pressure","Increased lymphatic drainage","Increased plasma oncotic pressure","Increased capillary hydrostatic pressure"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EStarling forces govern fluid movement across capillary membranes. These forces include hydrostatic pressure (pushing fluid out) and oncotic pressure (pulling fluid in).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased capillary hydrostatic pressure\u003C/strong\u003E causes peripheral oedema by forcing excess fluid into the interstitial space. This occurs in heart failure and venous insufficiency.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased plasma volume\u003C/strong\u003E triggers compensatory mechanisms to retain fluid within vessels and does not cause oedema.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased capillary hydrostatic pressure\u003C/strong\u003E reduces fluid movement into the interstitial space and prevents oedema formation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased lymphatic drainage\u003C/strong\u003E removes excess interstitial fluid and helps prevent oedema.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased plasma oncotic pressure\u003C/strong\u003E draws fluid into blood vessels and reduces oedema formation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Starling forces determine fluid movement between intravascular and interstitial spaces through hydrostatic and oncotic pressure gradients.","Increased capillary hydrostatic pressure is a key mechanism causing peripheral oedema in conditions like heart failure.","Understanding Starling forces helps identify the pathophysiology of oedema in clinical conditions."],"references":["Goyal A, Cusick AS, Bhutta BS. Peripheral Edema. 2023 Aug 17. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32119339.","Scallan J, Huxley VH, Korthuis RJ. Capillary Fluid Exchange: Regulation, Functions, and Pathology. San Rafael (CA): Morgan \u0026 Claypool Life Sciences; 2010. Chapter 4, Pathophysiology of Edema Formation. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK53445/","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"46922"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15460"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"46922","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/46922"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-15T16:17:24+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-15T16:21:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8151"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61471"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember